:::summary
Quantum mechanics is the branch of physics that describes the behavior of matter and energy at the atomic and subatomic scale. Developed in the early 20th century by Niels Bohr, Werner Heisenberg, Erwin Schrödinger, and others, it replaced classical physics at small scales and revealed a world governed by probability, wave-particle duality, and fundamental uncertainty. Quantum mechanics underlies chemistry, modern electronics, lasers, and our deepest understanding of nature.
